Leaning One-Arm Rear Delt Raise is an effective isolation exercise for targeting the posterior deltoid, enhancing shoulder definition and improving posture.&nbsp;&nbsp;
Setup: Stand next to a cable machine with the handle at the lowest setting. Use your non-working hand to grip the rack or bench for support. Reach across your body with the working arm, holding the handle.&nbsp;
Execution: With a slight bend in the elbow, raise the arm out to the side and slightly backward until it’s parallel to the floor. Focus on squeezing the rear delt at the top, then lower slowly to control the eccentric phase.&nbsp;
Benefits: This variation increases the stretch and contraction in the rear delts, promotes unilateral strength balance, and reduces reliance on momentum. It’s ideal for correcting muscular imbalances and improving shoulder health.&nbsp;
Form Tips: Keep your core engaged, avoid shrugging your shoulders, and maintain a controlled tempo—especially on the lowering phase. Use lighter weights to prioritize mind-muscle connection over load.&nbsp;
This exercise is also known as the leaning cable rear delt raise or one-arm rear lateral raise with lean, and can be adapted using dumbbells or a bench for support.
